"Smith S.V., Sleezer R.O., Renwick W.H., Buddemeier R.W.","Fates of eroded soil organic carbon: Mississippi Basin case study",2005,"Ecological Applications","15","6",,"1929","1940",,,10.1890/05-0073,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-30944462159&partnerID=40&md5=e631a90b3890e6765f986503c410a7ae","Departamento de Ecología, Centro de Investigación Científica Y de Educación Superior de Ensenada, Ensenada, Baja California 22860, Mexico; Earth Science Department, Emporia State University, Emporia, KS 66801, United States; Department of Geography, Miami University, Oxford, OH 45056, United States; Kansas Geological Survey, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66047, United States","Smith, S.V., Departamento de Ecología, Centro de Investigación Científica Y de Educación Superior de Ensenada, Ensenada, Baja California 22860, Mexico; Sleezer, R.O., Earth Science Department, Emporia State University, Emporia, KS 66801, United States; Renwick, W.H., Department of Geography, Miami University, Oxford, OH 45056, United States; Buddemeier, R.W., Kansas Geological Survey, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66047, United States","We have developed a mass balance analysis of organic carbon (OC) across the five major river subsystems of the Mississippi (MS) Basin (an area of 3.2 × 106 km2). This largely agricultural landscape undergoes a bulk soil erosion rate of ∼480 t·km -2·yr-1 (∼1500 × 106 t/yr, across the MS Basin), and a soil organic carbon (SOC) erosion rate of ∼7 t·km-2·yr-1 (∼22 × 106 t/yr). Erosion translocates upland SOC to alluvial deposits, water impoundments, and the ocean. Soil erosion is generally considered to be a net source of CO2 release to the atmosphere in global budgets. However, our results indicate that SOC erosion and relocation of soil apparently can reduce the net SOC oxidation rate of the original upland SOC while promoting net replacement of eroded SOC in upland soils that were eroded. Soil erosion at the MS Basin scale is, therefore, a net CO2 sink rather than a source. © 2005 by the Ecological Society of America.","CO2; Erosion; Mississippi Basin; Regional budget; Soil fertility; Soil organic carbon","agricultural land; carbon dioxide; mass balance; organic carbon; soil erosion",,,,,,"Aguilar, R., Heil, R.D., Soil organic carbon, nitrogen, and phosphorus quantities in northern Great Plains rangeland (1988) Soil Science Society of America Journal, 52, pp. 1076-1081; Amundson, R., The carbon budget in soils (2001) Annual Review of Earth and Planetary Sciences, 29, pp. 535-562; Bajracharya, R.M., Lal, R., Kimble, J.M., Diurnal and seasonal CO2-C flux from soil as related to erosion phases in central Ohio (2000) Soil Science Society of America Journal, 64, pp. 286-293; Bohn, H.L., Estimate of organic carbon in world soils: II (1982) Soil Science Society of America Proceedings, 46, pp. 1118-1119; Brubaker, S.C., Jones, A.J., Lewis, D.T., Frank, K., Soil properties associated with landscape position (1993) Soil Science Society of America Journal, 57, pp. 235-239; Church, M., Slaymaker, O., Disequilibrium of Holocene sediment yield in glaciated British Columbia (1989) Nature, 337, pp. 452-454; Cole, J.J., Caraco, N.F., Carbon in catchments: Connecting terrestrial carbon losses with aquatic metabolism (2001) Marine and Freshwater Research, 52, pp. 101-110; Cole, J.J., Caraco, N.F., Kling, G.W., Kratz, T.K., Carbon dioxide supersaturation in the surface waters of lakes (1994) Science, 265, pp. 1568-1570; Dean, W.E., Gorham, E., Magnitude and significance of carbon burial in lakes, reservoirs, and peatlands (1998) Geology, 26, pp. 535-538; Dearing, J.A., Jones, R.T., Coupling temporal and spatial dimensions of global sediment flux through lake and marine sediment records (2003) Global and Planetary Change, 39, pp. 147-168; Eswaran, H., Van Den Berg, E., Reich, P., Organic carbon in soils of the world (1993) Soil Science Society of America Journal, 57, pp. 192-194; Hanson, P.C., Pollard, A.I., Bade, D.L., Predick, K., Carpenter, S.R., Foley, J.A., A model of carbon evasion and sedimentation in temperate lakes (2004) Global Change Biology, 10, pp. 1285-1298; Harden, J.W., Sharpe, J.M., Parton, W.J., Ojima, D.S., Fries, T.L., Huntington, T.G., Dabney, S.M., Dynamic replacement and loss of soil carbon on eroding cropland (1999) Global Biogeochemical Cycles, 13, pp. 885-901; Jenny, H., (1941) Factors of Soil Formation, , McGraw-Hill, New York, New York, USA; Jobbagy, E.G., Jackson, R.B., The vertical distribution of soil organic carbon and its relation to climate and vegetation (2000) Ecological Applications, 10, pp. 423-432; Kleiss, H.J., Hillslope sedimentation and soil formation in northeastern Iowa (1970) Soil Science Society of America Proceedings, 34, pp. 287-290; Lal, R., Global soil erosion by water and carbon dynamics (1995) Soils and Global Change, pp. 131-142. , R. Lal, J. Kimble, E. Levine, and B. A. Stewart, editors. CRC Press, Boca Raton, Florida, USA; Lal, R., Soil erosion and the global carbon budget (2003) Environment International, 29, pp. 437-450; Lal, R., Soil carbon sequestration impacts on global climate change and food security (2004) Science, 304, pp. 1623-1627; Lal, R., Griffin, M., Apt, J., Lave, L., Morgan, M.G., Managing soil carbon (2004) Science, 304, p. 393; Liu, S., Bliss, N., Sundquist, E., Huntington, T.G., Modeling carbon dynamics in vegetation and soil under the impact of soil erosion and deposition (2003) Global Biogeochemical Cycles, 17, p. 1074. , 〈doi:10.1029/2002GB002010〉; Martel, Y.A., Paul, E.A., The use of radiocarbon dating of organic matter in the study of soil genesis (1974) Soil Science Society of America Proceedings, 38, pp. 501-506; Meade, R.H., Yuzyk, T.R., Day, T.J., Movement and storage of sediment in rivers of the United States and Canada (1990) Surface Water Hydrology, Geology of North America, O-1, pp. 255-280. , M. G. Wolman and H. C. Riggs, editors. Geological Society of America, Boulder, Colorado, USA; Milliman, J.D.